## 16. Future Architecture Extensions

These are natural evolution paths beyond the current POC:

```mermaid
flowchart LR
    POC[Beecon Client POC] --> API[Beecon Backend API]
    API --> DB[(Cloud DB<br/>reports · routes · users)]
    API --> PROXY[API Key Proxy<br/>Gemini · ORS]
    API --> PUSH[Push notifications<br/>hazard alerts]
    POC --> REAL[Live accessibility feeds<br/>OpenStreetMap · city data]
```

| Extension | Benefit |
|-----------|---------|
| Backend API | Secure API keys, shared community reports |
| Real-time hazard sync | Cross-user report visibility |
| Profile auth | Saved preferences across devices |
| OSM / city open data | Replace hardcoded BGC features |
| Push alerts | Safety advisories near user location |

---

## 17. Key Design Decisions

1. **Split routing API from scoring** — OSRM draws paths; local engine produces accessible/safe route cards with rich metadata. Allows demo without perfect ORS accessibility profiles.

2. **Dual score system** — Accessibility (mobility barriers) and Safety (time, crowd, security, AI advisories) are independent models combined into an Overall score.

3. **Offline-first reports** — Community reporting works without backend; critical for hackathon reliability.

4. **Web-first routing** — OSRM avoids ORS CORS/key issues in Chrome demos.

5. **Feature-first folders** — Scales cleanly as auth, routing, and map subsystems grow.

